because I just came
from Sutter's.

486
00:17:15,584 --> 00:17:17,865
I take it he told you about
our little conversation today.

487
00:17:17,906 --> 00:17:20,407
If, by conversation,
you mean going behind my back

488
00:17:20,442 --> 00:17:21,875
and getting his
investment business,

489
00:17:21,910 --> 00:17:23,243
then yeah, he told me.

490
00:17:23,278 --> 00:17:24,944
I didn't go behind your back.

491
00:17:24,980 --> 00:17:26,546
I saw an opportunity,
and I took it.

492
00:17:26,581 --> 00:17:29,616
Well, now he's seeing an
opportunity, and he's taking it.

493
00:17:29,651 --> 00:17:32,052
- What are you talking about?
- He's leveraging what you did

494
00:17:32,087 --> 00:17:35,055
to get me to move
for an immediate dismissal.

495
00:17:35,091 --> 00:17:37,236
And, don't tell me,
you think it's gonna work?

496
00:17:37,238 --> 00:17:38,337
I sure as hell do.

497
00:17:38,373 --> 00:17:40,339
And the second it does,
Mike's chance

498
00:17:40,375 --> 00:17:42,709
at getting out goes with it,
thanks to you.

499
00:17:42,744 --> 00:17:44,877
Hang on there, tiger.

500
00:17:44,913 --> 00:17:47,346
You're not in this position
because of something I did.

501
00:17:47,362 --> 00:17:49,028
You're in it
because of Sutter,

502
00:17:49,063 --> 00:17:51,130
and he'd be demanding
you have this case dismissed

503
00:17:51,165 --> 00:17:52,865
whether we have his
other business or not.

504
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:55,368
- Oh, that's not the point.
- No, Harvey, the point is,

505
00:17:55,403 --> 00:17:56,969
I have been out there
busting my ass

506
00:17:57,005 --> 00:17:59,672
trying to find us
new business for days,

507
00:17:59,707 --> 00:18:01,443
and do you know
what they keep asking?

508
00:18:01,543 --> 00:18:03,609
Why don't we have
Sutter's investment business.

509
00:18:03,645 --> 00:18:05,912
Goddamn right.
We needed it.

510
00:18:05,947 --> 00:18:09,949
I got it, and now
they're not asking anymore.

511
00:18:10,368 --> 00:18:12,469
Well, what's gonna happen
when we lose this case,

512
00:18:12,504 --> 00:18:13,837
and his business goes away?

513
00:18:13,872 --> 00:18:17,073
What happens is, we're already
built back up by then,

514
00:18:17,109 --> 00:18:18,842
so instead of blaming me

515
00:18:18,877 --> 00:18:20,677
for the position Sutter
has put you in,

516
00:18:20,712 --> 00:18:21,878
I suggest you go ahead

517
00:18:21,913 --> 00:18:24,547
and find yourself
a way out of it.

518
00:18:24,583 --> 00:18:29,986
<i>♪ ♪</i>

519
00:18:30,366 --> 00:18:32,567
Rachel,
what can I do for you?

520
00:18:32,602 --> 00:18:35,236
I was hoping you could
do something for Leonard Bailey.

521
00:18:35,271 --> 00:18:37,405
I drafted a motion
to reopen his case,

522
00:18:37,440 --> 00:18:39,440
but I need a current member
of the Bar to file it.

523
00:18:39,810 --> 00:18:40,887
And what happened
to the person

524
00:18:40,911 --> 00:18:42,210
you said
was gonna take this on?

525
00:18:42,245 --> 00:18:43,589
She can't get to it
till later this week,

526
00:18:43,613 --> 00:18:45,260
but I want to get on this
as soon as possible.

527
00:18:45,284 --> 00:18:46,884
Rachel, I'm sorry,
but I told you before,

528
00:18:46,919 --> 00:18:49,085
I don't have the resources
to work on this case now.

529
00:18:49,087 --> 00:18:50,898
Professor, this man has a wife
who gave up on him

530
00:18:50,922 --> 00:18:53,456
and children
that he doesn't see.

531
00:18:53,543 --> 00:18:55,777
His entire life
is passing him by,

532
00:18:55,812 --> 00:18:58,379
and the only way for him
to start getting it back

533
00:18:58,415 --> 00:19:01,583
is to just have someone
who cares enough about him

534
00:19:01,618 --> 00:19:06,588
that they give him
a half hour of their time.

535
00:19:07,023 --> 00:19:09,957
Let me see your motion.

536
00:19:16,432 --> 00:19:19,700
[exhales sharply]
This is well drafted.

537
00:19:19,736 --> 00:19:21,135
Thank you.

538
00:19:21,745 --> 00:19:24,413
But I'm afraid it won't work.

539
00:19:24,448 --> 00:19:25,814
What are you talking--no--

540
00:19:25,850 --> 00:19:27,427
look, there's no reason that
he should have been convicted.

541
00:19:27,451 --> 00:19:29,262
Look at the evidence.
That's not the point, Rachel.

542
00:19:29,286 --> 00:19:31,486
I've worked on dozens
of these cases,

543
00:19:31,522 --> 00:19:33,133
and like it or not,
the standard to reopen

544
00:19:33,157 --> 00:19:34,823
is higher than what it says
in the books.

545
00:19:34,859 --> 00:19:38,393
You need something undeniable.

546
00:19:38,429 --> 00:19:39,928
Then what am I supposed to do?

547
00:19:39,964 --> 00:19:43,298
You're supposed to use your
gumption to find that something,

548
00:19:43,334 --> 00:19:45,834
and get Leonard Bailey the
justice he's been waiting for.

549
00:19:50,412 --> 00:19:52,979
Harvey, it's late.
Whatever you're doing here

550
00:19:53,015 --> 00:19:54,392
is gonna have to wait
until morning.

551
00:19:54,416 --> 00:19:56,383
- It can't.
- Why's that?

552
00:19:56,418 --> 00:19:58,885
Because Sutter wants me to
move for an immediate dismissal.

553
00:19:58,920 --> 00:20:00,120
What?

554
00:20:00,155 --> 00:20:01,432
You leveraged me
into bringing this indictment,

555
00:20:01,456 --> 00:20:02,656
and now you want to toss it?

556
00:20:02,691 --> 00:20:05,091
I don't want to toss it,
but if I don't,

557
00:20:05,127 --> 00:20:06,860
he's gonna find
someone else who will.

558
00:20:06,895 --> 00:20:08,461
What are you
doing here, Harvey?

559
00:20:08,497 --> 00:20:10,630
Nothing, I'm just finishing
my dinner.

560
00:20:11,381 --> 00:20:13,214
The thing is,
I don't like to litter,

561
00:20:13,249 --> 00:20:14,482
so why don't you
do me a favor?

562
00:20:14,517 --> 00:20:18,986
If I forget this when I go,

563
00:20:19,022 --> 00:20:21,055
why don't you take it upstairs
and throw it away?

564
00:20:21,090 --> 00:20:22,656
What's in the bag, Harvey?

565
00:20:22,692 --> 00:20:25,259
A wrapper, couple napkins,

566
00:20:25,294 --> 00:20:26,494
and a few extra fries.

567
00:20:26,529 --> 00:20:28,362
What the hell is
in the bag, Harvey?

568
00:20:28,398 --> 00:20:29,964
What you needed to keep
this case going,

569
00:20:29,999 --> 00:20:31,199
and I stopped you
from getting.

570
00:20:31,234 --> 00:20:32,778
Damn it, you said
you were gonna defend him

571
00:20:32,802 --> 00:20:35,002
to the best of your ability.
And I meant it.

572
00:20:35,038 --> 00:20:37,338
But I also knew,
if push came to shove,

573
00:20:37,373 --> 00:20:39,907
I'd do what
I had to to get Mike out,

574
00:20:39,942 --> 00:20:41,308
and I made my peace with it.

575
00:20:41,344 --> 00:20:43,010
- Yeah, well, I haven't.
- Yes, you have.

576
00:20:43,046 --> 00:20:44,857
- What are you talking about?
- You've been giving me

577
00:20:44,881 --> 00:20:47,782
this song and dance
about not colluding,

578
00:20:47,817 --> 00:20:49,950
and it didn't matter
what I said back to you,

579
00:20:49,986 --> 00:20:53,054
as long as it was something
to let you believe we wouldn't.

580
00:20:53,089 --> 00:20:56,023
Because that song wasn't for me,
it was for you.

581
00:20:56,059 --> 00:20:58,559
- Oh, for me? Bullshit.
- I don't think so, Sean,

582
00:20:58,594 --> 00:20:59,860
because you don't break a guy

583
00:20:59,896 --> 00:21:03,264
out of prison
just to advance your career.

584
00:21:03,299 --> 00:21:06,167
Look, this means something
to you.

585
00:21:06,202 --> 00:21:07,413
I don't need to know
what it is,

586
00:21:07,437 --> 00:21:08,969
but it means something
to me too,

587
00:21:09,005 --> 00:21:11,072
so let's just admit
that we're in this together

588
00:21:11,107 --> 00:21:13,374
and get this thing done.

589
00:21:13,409 --> 00:21:16,243
Take that garbage
and throw it away.

590
00:21:16,279 --> 00:21:20,281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

591
00:21:26,477 --> 00:21:28,978
Now can I have champagne?

592
00:21:29,013 --> 00:21:30,724
You got the realtor to
give you the key to the house.

593
00:21:30,748 --> 00:21:33,015
Not only that, I got him
to agree to take the Kellmans

594
00:21:33,051 --> 00:21:34,550
to brunch tomorrow
from 10:00 to 2:00

595
00:21:34,586 --> 00:21:36,185
to celebrate their big sale.

596
00:21:36,617 --> 00:21:37,816
Well, that is great,
Donna,

597
00:21:37,851 --> 00:21:39,195
but I don't just need
to get into the house.

598
00:21:39,219 --> 00:21:41,586
I need Tara to believe that
it's my house, which means--

599
00:21:41,622 --> 00:21:43,633
No lock box on the door,
no for sale sign in the yard,

600
00:21:43,657 --> 00:21:45,201
and no personal
belongings in the house,

601
00:21:45,225 --> 00:21:47,626
which is why we are
gonna be there at 10:01

602
00:21:47,661 --> 00:21:49,194
to stage the shit
out of that place.

603
00:21:49,382 --> 00:21:52,283
Oh, and these
are coming with us.

604
00:21:54,821 --> 00:21:56,788
You reframed pictures
of Bruno?

605
00:21:57,201 --> 00:21:59,001
In the style of the house.

606
00:21:59,036 --> 00:22:03,238
And not just Bruno...

607
00:22:03,274 --> 00:22:05,307
Mikado.

608
00:22:05,696 --> 00:22:07,363
That's perfect, Donna.

609
00:22:07,398 --> 00:22:09,098
I just thought showing Tara
your wood

610
00:22:09,133 --> 00:22:11,801
wasn't the only way to show her
what kind of man you are.

611
00:22:11,836 --> 00:22:12,968
Thank you, Donna.

612
00:22:13,004 --> 00:22:14,837
You're welcome, Louis.

613
00:22:19,421 --> 00:22:20,687
Since when do we get a room

614
00:22:20,722 --> 00:22:23,356
instead of having to use
those damn phones?

615
00:22:23,391 --> 00:22:27,193
Since I officially
became part of your legal team.

616
00:22:27,228 --> 00:22:28,561
- My legal team?
- That's right.

617
00:22:28,596 --> 00:22:31,230
The firm that I work for
is taking your case.

618
00:22:35,512 --> 00:22:39,347
After all this time.

619
00:22:39,382 --> 00:22:41,983
Thank you.

620
00:22:42,018 --> 00:22:44,552
You're welcome.

621
00:22:44,588 --> 00:22:46,988
But we still need
to get the case reopened,

622
00:22:47,023 --> 00:22:50,425
and to do that we need
to find something new.

623
00:22:50,460 --> 00:22:51,968
So where do we get that?

624
00:22:52,068 --> 00:22:53,612
I was going through
the state's case file,

625
00:22:53,636 --> 00:22:55,403
and I read your police report.

626
00:22:55,438 --> 00:22:57,371
You said there was a woman
with you that night

627
00:22:57,407 --> 00:23:00,620
who can testify that you didn't
kill that couple.

628
00:23:00,720 --> 00:23:04,555
That's right, Maria,
but that's not new.

629
00:23:04,590 --> 00:23:06,430
Well, it's new as far
as the court's concerned,

630
00:23:06,459 --> 00:23:08,730
because it was never
admitted at trial.

631
00:23:08,830 --> 00:23:10,897
- Well, let's admit it.
- It's not that easy.

632
00:23:10,932 --> 00:23:12,710
I need to understand
why it was never admitted.

633
00:23:12,734 --> 00:23:16,770
Because the damn woman up
and disappeared before my trial.

634
00:23:16,805 --> 00:23:18,471
My lawyer didn't do a thing.

635
00:23:18,507 --> 00:23:20,073
You had an alibi witness,

636
00:23:20,108 --> 00:23:21,748
and your public defender
let her get away.

637
00:23:21,777 --> 00:23:23,076
That's what I've been saying.

638
00:23:23,111 --> 00:23:25,178
Maria could have told the jury
that I didn't do it,

639
00:23:25,213 --> 00:23:26,746
instead no one told them.

640
00:23:26,782 --> 00:23:29,315
Two weeks later,
I'm in here,

641
00:23:29,351 --> 00:23:31,518
and I've been here
ever since.

642
00:23:31,553 --> 00:23:35,522
Is there anything else
I need to know?

643
00:23:35,890 --> 00:23:38,724
Then I need to find
Maria Gomez.

644
00:23:46,200 --> 00:23:48,801
Look, man, please,
I really don't want to talk.

645
00:23:48,836 --> 00:23:51,337
Good, 'cause
I want you to listen.

646
00:23:54,876 --> 00:23:59,211
When I was a kid,
I thought we had it good.

647
00:23:59,247 --> 00:24:01,847
And we did. Had a nice house,
nice neighborhood.

648
00:24:02,347 --> 00:24:05,081
Except for one thing.

649
00:24:05,116 --> 00:24:08,217
Turns out my father...

650
00:24:08,253 --> 00:24:09,886
was a criminal.

651
00:24:10,050 --> 00:24:12,117
One day he got caught.
He went to prison.

652
00:24:12,153 --> 00:24:14,353
My whole life fell apart.

653
00:24:14,389 --> 00:24:16,989
How old were you?

654
00:24:17,025 --> 00:24:19,458
15.

655
00:24:19,494 --> 00:24:21,260
I'll tell you something.

656
00:24:21,295 --> 00:24:24,330
I hated that man for doing
what he did to me,

657
00:24:24,365 --> 00:24:27,633
so I did what messed up
15-year-olds do.

658
00:24:27,668 --> 00:24:31,137
- Started acting out.
- Acting out?

659
00:24:31,887 --> 00:24:37,057
Brother, I was on my way
to a place worse than this.

660
00:24:37,092 --> 00:24:39,392
Finally, my mom made me
see someone,

661
00:24:39,428 --> 00:24:41,595
and he helped me realize

662
00:24:41,630 --> 00:24:45,499
that if I didn't change,
I was gonna ruin my life.

663
00:24:45,534 --> 00:24:48,201
So I straightened out
and turned my life around.

664
00:24:48,663 --> 00:24:50,663
And that's why you do
what you do.

665
00:24:50,698 --> 00:24:54,033
Yeah.

666
00:24:54,068 --> 00:24:56,068
- Why are you telling me this?
- Because the way

667
00:24:56,103 --> 00:24:59,772
that man got through to me
was to open up about himself,

668
00:24:59,807 --> 00:25:03,209
and I realized that if
I really want to help you,

669
00:25:03,244 --> 00:25:05,644
I got to do the same.

670
00:25:05,680 --> 00:25:08,581
<i>[tense music]</i>

671
00:25:08,616 --> 00:25:12,384
<i>♪ ♪</i>

672
00:25:12,876 --> 00:25:14,742
All right, I dragged this out
as long as I can,

673
00:25:14,778 --> 00:25:16,422
but I'm pretty much done
drafting this motion.

674
00:25:16,446 --> 00:25:17,712
So I'll need you to proof it--

675
00:25:17,747 --> 00:25:18,824
Harvey, before I do that,
I think you should take

676
00:25:18,848 --> 00:25:20,381
a look at these.

677
00:25:20,614 --> 00:25:22,513
- What is it?
- Cahill issued subpoenas

678
00:25:22,549 --> 00:25:24,682
to deposition William Sutter
and Kevin Miller.

679
00:25:24,718 --> 00:25:27,518
- That sneaky son of a bitch.
- Why are you smiling?

680
00:25:27,554 --> 00:25:28,953
Because last night
I went to Cahill

681
00:25:28,989 --> 00:25:31,823
and tried to give him
Sutter's trading program.

682
00:25:32,057 --> 00:25:33,623
- You did what?
- It was the only way

683
00:25:33,659 --> 00:25:35,992
I could see to stop the case
from getting dismissed,

684
00:25:36,028 --> 00:25:37,094
but he wouldn't take it.

685
00:25:37,642 --> 00:25:39,108
And this buys you time.

686
00:25:39,143 --> 00:25:41,377
It does, if the judge
waits to rule on our motion

687
00:25:41,412 --> 00:25:44,046
until after Cahill conducts
these depositions.

688
00:25:44,082 --> 00:25:46,160
Harvey, even if that works,
what if Cahill doesn't get

689
00:25:46,184 --> 00:25:48,162
enough from the depositions
to keep the case alive?

690
00:25:48,186 --> 00:25:50,064
Then Mike's chance of getting
out of prison is gone,

691
00:25:50,088 --> 00:25:51,721
which means Cahill's
not the only one

692
00:25:51,756 --> 00:25:54,924
that needs to use this
to try and get something.

693
00:25:57,838 --> 00:25:59,504
I have to admit, Ms. Zane,
when you said

694
00:25:59,566 --> 00:26:01,778
you were looking into the Bailey
case, my interest was piqued.

695
00:26:01,802 --> 00:26:04,002
That was a long time ago.

696
00:26:04,037 --> 00:26:05,482
Well, you've obviously
come a long way

697
00:26:05,506 --> 00:26:07,272
since your public defender days.

698
00:26:07,307 --> 00:26:10,408
You don't exactly see the best
of humanity at that job,

699
00:26:10,444 --> 00:26:12,911
which makes it one
you can only do for so long.

700
00:26:12,946 --> 00:26:15,247
But you didn't come here
to be my therapist.

701
00:26:15,282 --> 00:26:18,316
No, I came to talk
about Maria Gomez.

702
00:26:18,352 --> 00:26:19,551
What about her?

703
00:26:19,586 --> 00:26:21,620
I'm curious as to how you
can have an alibi witness

704
00:26:21,655 --> 00:26:22,621
on a murder case,

705
00:26:22,656 --> 00:26:24,096
and your client ends up
on death row.

706
00:26:24,203 --> 00:26:26,103
Because I didn't have
an alibi witness.

707
00:26:26,138 --> 00:26:27,971
I had a no-show
who vanished into thin air,

708
00:26:28,007 --> 00:26:30,150
and I didn't have the resources
to find her.

709
00:26:30,250 --> 00:26:32,250
And you didn't think
to ask the police at trial

710
00:26:32,285 --> 00:26:34,252
why they didn't follow up
on Leonard's alibi?

711
00:26:34,287 --> 00:26:35,386
I did think of it,

712
00:26:35,422 --> 00:26:36,966
and they would have said
what they always say,

713
00:26:36,990 --> 00:26:39,101
"Every murderer claims
to have an alibi,"

714
00:26:39,201 --> 00:26:41,235
and if I couldn't produce her,
why should they?

715
00:26:41,270 --> 00:26:42,814
Well, you could have
at least asked for postponement,

716
00:26:42,838 --> 00:26:44,071
to have time to find her.

717
00:26:44,106 --> 00:26:45,739
And I would have,
except for one thing.

718
00:26:45,774 --> 00:26:48,075
I wasn't sure a drug addict
with a prior conviction

719
00:26:48,110 --> 00:26:50,310
would have done
Leonard Bailey much good.

720
00:26:50,722 --> 00:26:52,855
That's about her character,
not the facts of the case.

721
00:26:52,890 --> 00:26:55,224
Her character is
a fact of the case,

722
00:26:55,259 --> 00:26:56,670
and when I pressed her
as to what the two of them

723
00:26:56,694 --> 00:26:58,105
were doing at the time
of those murders,

724
00:26:58,129 --> 00:27:00,096
she admitted they were
both on meth,

725
00:27:00,131 --> 00:27:01,564
and it wasn't the first time.

726
00:27:01,599 --> 00:27:03,599
Which, by the way,
might have something to do with

727
00:27:03,635 --> 00:27:06,068
why she never
showed up at trial.

728
00:27:06,549 --> 00:27:09,450
